We then assessed microbial composition among age groups. The LD/nLD ratio increased with age, driven largely by increasing CST-LI microbiomes, with decreasing CST-GV and CST-PM microbiomes (Figure 2A
). Compared to women aged 25–41 years, those in the age groups 18–19 years and 20–24 years were more likely to have an nLD microbiome (odds ratio [OR], 1.65 [95% confidence interval {CI}, 1.02–2.65], P = .028; OR, 1.40 [95% CI, 1.01–1.95], P = .030, respectively) (Figure 2B
) and CST-PM relative to a CST-LC microbiome (OR, 3.14 [95% CI, 1.12–7.87], P = .017; OR, 2.81 [95% CI, 1.07–7.09], P = .038, respectively) (Figure 2C
). Except for CST-PM, the distributions of other CSTs relative to CST-LC were similar across age groups. At the genus level, we observed an increasing proportion of BVAB, including Megasphaera (r = −0.087, P = .023, adjusted P = .45) and Atopobium (r = −0.075, P = .0495, adjusted P = .45), with decreasing age. However, only Megasphaera was more prevalent in women aged 18–19 years compared to those aged 25–41 years (log2 fold difference = 1.72, P = .0023, adjusted P = .0498). Younger age was also associated with increased prevalence of inflammatory bacterial pathways, including propanoate (r = −0.090, P = .020, adjusted P = .41) and butanoate metabolism (r = −0.086, P = .027, adjusted P = .41). In a multivariable logistic regression analysis to control for differences in clinical, behavioral, and demographic variables (Table 2), nLD vaginal microbiomes remained significantly higher in the age groups 18–19 years and 20–24 years (OR, 2.08 [95% CI, 1.28–3.54], P = .007; OR, 1.67 [95% CI, 1.16–2.42], P = .006, respectively). HSV-2 infection at baseline was associated with increased non-Lactobacillus microbiomes, but HSV-2 infection was much lower in younger age groups (Table 1), and non-Lactobacillus microbiomes remained higher in women aged 18–19 years and 20–24 years when stratified into HSV-2–seropositive (OR, 1.97 [95% CI, .88–4.33], P = .0628; OR, 1.58 [95% CI, .4–2.51], P = .0272, respectively) or HSV-2–seronegative groups (OR, 2.083 [95% CI, 1.01–4.16], P = .0331; OR, 1.68 [95% CI, .92–3.04], P = .0546, respectively). DMPA use was associated with decreased non-Lactobacillus microbiomes in a multivariate model. However, younger women reported increased usage of DMPA, and a further subanalysis using serum medroxyprogesterone actetate (MPA) levels, which we measured previously [26] (Supplementary Methods), showed that higher MPA was associated with lower non-Lactobacillus microbiomes (high/medium vs low/undetectable MPA: OR, 0.705 [95% CI, .48–1.05], P = .075), which was not statistically significant. Overall, differences in these variables could not explain increased non-Lactobacillus microbiomes in younger women.
